A Republican Strategy to Hinder Obama's Re-Election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight voter fraud.
Now, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and states that voter fraud is less prevalent in the United States than the number of people who die from lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will adversely affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, the American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And along the same lines, a majority of American governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that hindered the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon has spread following the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 restricting the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID in addition to proof of U.S. citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of counting and remove citizens with criminal records from their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
The State of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
Therefore, the Republican authorities were quick to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as a Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 did not have such an identity document.
But, often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
As a result, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
Indeed, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 and 20 per cent of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states, students, the voters who vote most for Democratic candidates, cannot use their institution-issued photo ID.
On the other hand, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs that usually vote Republican parties to use documents issued by those clubs.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers in 2011 supported certain laws that abolished same-day voter registration in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to set up a help desk for voters who wanted to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration drives contributed to the registration of some 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 resulted in the registration rate of new voters falling in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers adopted laws in five other states favoring reducing the period of early voting.
For example, in the 2008 elections in Florida, 33% of voters who voted early were African-American, while the latter represented only 13% of the state's electorate.
In the case of Hispanics, exactly the same thing happened.
They represent only 11% of voters, equivalent to 24% of citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, represent only 46% of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have fervently opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney's Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
It could, in part, limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring photo IDs.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of voting rights in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, since it is clear that they are intended to influence the results of 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have adopted such laws account for 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will adversely affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
