The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated a great deal of commotion last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
What's more, it's about the particle whose existence the Standard Model predicted: our better or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been observed empirically.
But it's not entirely clear to physicists that it's Higgs.
We know without a doubt that a new particle exists and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data is still needed to be completely certain.
Anyway, we assume that it is Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem small. We'll see what it's all about.
There is, in this great world, a generalized and inescapable law which implies that two things cannot meet in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that rule and do not try too much, because you will end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics in it: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; A "state" that consists, roughly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And on the other are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can meet in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories, which, by the way, is extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we will not talk about here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it should be emphasized here, are not the exotic bugs we might believe.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "particle of light" that acts as a "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; A bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave is born (light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon; that is, one of the "force-bearing" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it requires reaching extremely high energies, a bit like an icy pond in which only a thick rock could slide across the surface.
That is why it takes a huge particle accelerator like the one at CERN (the large hadron collider is a ring 27 km in circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The electromagnetic field analogy is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles and materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do it, but others don't: a piece of paper, for example, will never stand on its own sticking to a fridge door.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not.
Now, what "can all this research contribute", asks Mrs Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and MS predictions.
For their part, many fervently wish that they meet, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that covers certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation related to gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the Universe (another oops!).
But we have found no such differences at CERN so far.
Impact
The repercussions of such research on our day-to-day lives are difficult to predict, but we don't think we're wrong to say it won't have any.
Just so you can see: in the early 60s, the pioneers of lasers in laboratories did not suspect at all the revolution that their work would cause.
They glimpsed scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962, at first the laser was considered more of a "laboratory apparatus".
Imagine...
And in addition, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light collector in 1969 in the course of his research on optics.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this sensor now serves as an "eye" for all digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
That does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but that you never know...
Palliative care. The best way to die... | Le Devoir
In its Dying in Dignity Commission, Quebec recently debated the sensitive issue of the end of life.
The debate should resume soon while a bill is prepared.
Now, within that essential domain, there is still much to be done.
Le Devoir has tried to see it up close.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was destroying him had given him a two-year respite.
"I had been given five years to live, but I've been like this for seven," he says, lying on his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care centre in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, we can't be prepared for this," he continues.
The disease has wreaked havoc on him: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the bathroom alone and even eating on his own.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he resignedly accepts to be helped to eat.
Brave, he even smiles and talks to strangers who pay attention to him, bring him medicine and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to have my diarrhea cured, it's humiliating," she confesses.
A few hours later, the team found a remedy for that evil.
"In the course of our lives we learn that a man pees on his feet," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois center.
Returning to their childhood, for certain people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"That depends on the person's ability to accept that regression," he says.
Because, in the opinion of most people who work in palliative care, the great moments take place at the very heart of that regression.
All patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois palliative care facility suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life prognosis of three months.
In that state, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer offer "curative" care.
Ms. A.'s greatest fear, 89, is dying "conscious and drowning."
But the disease has made him discover his children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more desires left in this life," she says, before agreeing to have a mask put on to help her breathe.
And she expects, in the coming days, a last visit from her son who lives in Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois is offered, with a group of volunteers, the care of the body and help with food.
It is palliative care given when nothing else can be done.
To help make his death more comfortable.
In Quebec we have one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It is very little, since we know that we will all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the center.
Whether at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is offered mouthwashes with brandy or Pepsi, according to the lawsuit.
Diabetics no longer have their sugar levels monitored.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we poured a beer to Mr. X, who died in the course of the night.
This morning, his son finished the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help both patients and their loved ones," says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois centre, the days pass without ever being the same.
Next to a 94-year-old man savoring his last family gathering in the courtyard, well placed between his pillows while everyone drinks to his health, a 36-year-old dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two children, after having tried everything to survive.
"For six months now, there have always been three to five beds occupied by people under 45 with cancer," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to the Victor-Gadboisarrivent centre come from home and 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
77 per cent of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, meaning care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient reaches the terminal phase of their life, whether at home, in hospital or in a care facility.
And several agencies, such as the Victor-Gadbois center and the Grand Montréal home palliative care society, specialize almost exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great relative lack of health care in Quebec that makes many doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by eminent palliative care workers, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's healthcare system is not competent enough to ensure that everyone is entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
"Recently," he says, "I have seen a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room suffering great pain without having done what is necessary to relieve her.
I fear patients will want to die just because they don't receive proper care."
And at the same time, many oncologists persist with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognoses.
Hélène Richard's hopes of survival were already low when she stopped a grueling chemotherapy treatment.
"When I told my oncologist I wanted to stop treatment, she told me she was very sorry I wanted to stop fighting," she says.
"However, she had told me there was nothing else to do!"
There is no almighty care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who request to die thank their caregivers for not attending to their demands once their pain has been relieved thanks to a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is absolutely not all-powerful when it comes to pain management.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of home palliative care at Grand Montréal, patients do not respond to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors usually resort to palliative sedation, which serves to put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can't pretend we don't understand that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved disease will have the possibility of having that palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved all say the same thing: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want euthanasia," but "I want relief."
