- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from the movie "Iron Man", but also to any mere mortal.
There's a problem with this idea that critics often point out: there's no tactile response!
The hands don't feel anything!
What responses does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth could well be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand in quality of support for the image.
Register touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are truly aimed at bringing tangibility to these "images in the air". For example, the interference of various ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is located gives a sensation similar to what one feels if someone were blowing on your fingertips, but that sensation is still very weak.
There are also wristbands that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this is also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to trick the brain?
Make him think that he feels what he seems to feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here hides another challenge that we will have to struggle with for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space believe that he is going to an open, almost endless space. We are also working on the idea of treadmills (not like those in gyms), mobile platforms, as well as giant balloons.
For now, tricking the brain is not so easy, you still have to work for many years.
That is what makes working with virtual reality attractive to researchers, who are in a state of total conception.
