It needs to be said that even those countries we take as a model face a large number of problems.
If it wasn't so, it wouldn't be beneficial to collaborate with our office, wouldn't it?
With regard to the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean for your Office? Is its incidence manifested in any way?
Taking into account that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet manifested itself in the control actions.
Since we carry out ex-post checks, there needs to be a certain delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have initiated a new tool for "detection of non-economic risks", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, since the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process and the like are rectified.
Do you consider that the approval of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it is a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I believe that this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope that it will be so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulations "tighten" and that it is impossible to comply with them.
Already under the previous regulations, the persons controlled were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programmes of the regional council), and every law not respected in the field of public procurement meant the violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it then make sense to toughen the law in this way?
I think not this way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal mistake, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create more bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this path has begun.
The prime minister has recently stated that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, referring to the fact that it is autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc system banned or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits something, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the action of the Office that has the obligation to carry out such controls and demand obligations.
You can say, "We changed the law and allowed it," but you can't say what we will do as usual.
In the law on public procurement, the regulations are quite strict as to how to act formally. And that's how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This, in my opinion, is what we lack.
