Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency held last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second ESA member country of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began an intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in the agency's project committee.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld at the astronomical observatory in Warsaw in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the attendees indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prizes in France for their "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known throughout the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he named one of the craters on the far side of the moon.
Already in 1925 a dresina was built in Poland that was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and the details of the project are not known.
It is unclear whether the rocket was to be used to start the dresine or to brake.
The information about this dresina is limited to that collected in the press of the time.
From the year 1933 the Polish artillery began to devote itself to missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the research reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric fighter missile designed by the engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki, was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all projects for missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the start of the war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of the journal Problemy, society is referred to for the first time with four very extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, by Prof. M. Subotowicze, he proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
Artificial satellite projects had already been launched at that time and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
From the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in autumn of the same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902–1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA was significantly involved in the development of the MR sounding rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and first launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 aerial tests of the RM-2 two-stage rockets began in the Błędów desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have an apogee of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind wind.
However, in 1962 the work was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other by the space available for scientific apparatus.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The peak in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first aerial tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payweight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
Later the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention the entry of Poland into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the COSPAR national committee two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined the cosmic space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remek.
The suspension of the law on social work is not the solution.
Last week the constitutional court suspended the social traabajos law.
The resolution sparked heated discussion in society.
It will certainly be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in the labour cost (of wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and for this "causes a drop" in the price of the competitor with the aim of taking over most of the market and, in this way, increase its profit margin.
On a large scale it means, for most entrepreneurs, moving production abroad, buying there cheaper, or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in countries where the price of labour, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, with it, is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, state social spending necessarily grows.
All this situation favors the total disinterest of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and compensate for the economic and social damage they have caused in their eagerness to obtain benefits.
The situation is universally so well known that it is not necessary to present specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of those countries are forced to compete with the aim of artificially lowering the social level of the population itself and, in this way, attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own populations without taking into account social decline.
This is especially evident in the changes in existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of financial obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, through the restricted right of employees in terms of labor rights.
The result is growing poverty along with widening gap between rich and poor.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot support themselves with their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid has now reached one million.
In the context of the increased competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly frequent case: people employed with a salary so low that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind concerning the situation of auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
The cost-saving measures of virtually all the southern states of the EU undoubtedly lead to the same situation. People, pressured by an abysmal decline in their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the nineteenth century or to live on a terrible salary at the edge of society, in the hope that one day private investment capital will arrive in the country.
Is it necessary to ask yourself where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never arrives, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a tiny part of a European salary.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media claim ad nauseam that the state should not contribute capital to the economy, that running the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends tooth and nail the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by meddling in control.
Next, it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence with its egoism the political march and, therefore, the whole state.
In this case the answer is clearly yes.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the realm of corruption, in mutual favours, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany the situation is as follows: state ministries, in the absence of financial means, entrust the drafting of bills to private legal companies, which are often linked to industry.
Such bills are then passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation quickly find themselves in a situation such as the one described by Appianus in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the Time of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state had long disintegrated and administrations were occupied by force."
In exchange for bribes, illegitimately obtained favors and help to finance stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption spread unimpeded and people went to the polls with their votes in advance." "There were no people with character who aspired to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was eight months without consuls"... "It began to be spoken in earnest that the only remedy for such a serious situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man." Although Appianus thought of Pompeii, Caesar rose to power and forever transformed democracy into autocracy.
The conclusion, as in ancient times, is that today's society is based on inconsiderate preferences for individual benefit without regard for common interests.
Private capital is not capable, in its essence, of understanding and claiming the benefits of the whole society.
The result is the same as then, an unprecedented decline of the elite, without an effort to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems in favor of a democracy of the liberal type, as a definite pause, waiting for the next coup.
The truly devastating fact is that the current elite is completely ignorant of the losses of hundreds of thousands in lives, social and humanitarian catastrophes that we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and more recent history.
The suspension of the law on public procurement is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue looking for other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution lies in concrete socio-political reforms, which strengthen both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
