Argo Movie: If It Gets Raw, Call Hollywood
In November 1979 a group of Islamist student demonstrations occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned Shah Mohamed Reza Pahlavi, who after the revolution fled to the United States. The United States, which had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation offered no positive prospect: throwing the shah overboard could not afford it, since, if it did, it endangered the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within their reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was subsequently further intensified by the failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government's negotiating intervention.
In the US, his fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck thematizes an episode of this story, which reaped a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian embassy.
CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, for which a covert story helped an extravagant point: they left with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that examined the location in the country for the filming of a science fiction blockbuster.
Combination of genres
The plan drawn up by "exfiltration" expert Toni Mendez required the collaboration of Hollywood.
To make the lie seem truthful, the film project was written about in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictitious production company even had a real office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a hoax (an example can be the series Ocean's Eleven).
In the film moods are combined. We find on the one hand well-documented sequences from Tehran. The credits sequence shows emblematic photographs of the time of the events, which were captured in the same way in the film; There are not many differences in this regard.
On the other, typical Hollywood scenes somewhat lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And also, scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions: men in suits who analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, by telephone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Goodbye Small, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film in which the action does not take place in the city of Boston, where he grew up.
Likewise, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a characteristic that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck proves it in Argo, where Tehran is "rolling" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of true events. The introductory sequence of the embassy siege is impressive for its synoptic capacity that, at the same time, conveys the emotion of bewilderment and lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, the story takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the imposter team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story doesn't offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And he manages pretty well. Sometimes it adds something to reality: here everything does not go so elegantly (the scene in which the crisis lurks at the Tehran airport, the diversion of a call to America and the unbridled search behind its runway become crazy).
Argo's weakness is the lack of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are by no means the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses a bit of dramatic stroke, but it is a film that can be followed with moderate interest, assess its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70s.
But for it to collapse, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a true story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services can be, it is enough.
