The architecture studio MVRDV proves that real adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the recently completed "mountain of books" - 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it has a futuristic look, and there's finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby passing by on the street.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company near the library, says: "Plus, the building is beautiful."
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have internet, tablets and e-books.
No one enters those old-fashioned libraries for pleasure, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town at the gates of Rotterdam that is barely worth a fleeting visit, holds the dubious honour of having won a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counteract this shameful situation, some years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and to copy the seven fictitious bridges that are represented on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that's how policymakers decided that there was only one possibility to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar charts and responsible for fun and cynical buildings, took the subject with his usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked around in perplexity and shrugged, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size into a pyramid and concluded his short speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens,
Here you have it, my proposal for Spijkenisse's mountain of books, the so-called 'Boekenberg'."
Nine years later, the €30 million mountain is being erected in the planned spot.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and townhouse buildings.
At the beginning of November the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small city devoid of history, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white façade one would rather intuit a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to the Book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheese factory.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountain massif, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the annealed brick floor and elegant street lamps unmistakably support the public condition of the library.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
When you look up you can see the park benches, dogs and children playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Usually the bookshelves are arranged along the façade and in the center opens a huge dark room that is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we have done is turn the classic spatial configuration upside down and take the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention should be made of the black shelves that assume the functions of wall cladding, parapet and railing at the same time.
Sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even the most up-to-date architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that's how one day, on a Frisian farm, we came across the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands have used a plastic fabric a few millimeters thick as a base to hold the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This tissue lasts for two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, until obtaining plates of four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a mixture of new car and sneakers.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain the reward awaits us: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but in it you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Giving for a New Soul
"Although it is hard to believe given its large glass surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Despite the fact that the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden trusses located transversely to the glass façade serve to shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is a matter of automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there too.
Professor of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde has also visited the library. She calls the "Boekenberg" the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way it is intended to fill, for the moment, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; It currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has penetrated deeply.
The shelves are packed.
"There's nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows that your book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there to decorate.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved success in this queen discipline that in specialized jargon is known as "creation of an identity".
The town of Spijkenisse has written a piece of literary history.
Regardless of how young and uneducated she may be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a more prominent role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, this puts Berlin in a rather tricky diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier in the week, Germany hinted that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories observer state status to the United Nations.
However, Berlin eventually abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, because of the country's special relationship with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time I think it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising that took place in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yes, that's right.
This is because it is currently reorienting its foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to doing so.
I think they are still testing what their role will be, but they have already started down the road to a "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries like France or Great Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean concretely from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is strongly motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and by its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers and for that reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken on the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason it must be careful not to alienate itself from Arab public opinion or Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not attach so much importance to it since it is not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a fundamental role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the US by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been such a drastic rupture as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps in doing so Germany has managed to earn a certain respect.
After all, all this has only demonstrated that it is a country that they take seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
On the other hand, the US has been clearly in favour of a veto.
Is there a disparity of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of American domestic politics.
I think the Obama administration secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
But, because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot defend this position in public.
I believe that the real disparity of opinion does not really have the magnitude that is attributed to it.
