"Trademark protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a globally known brand and so is Polo Ralph Lauren.
But what is Armani Polo?
Behind this name hides a name officially registered in China but that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the true eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then it is not clear that they will be proved right.
"Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China," says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing who specializes in protection rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters to be able to register their trademarks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada Prada-Kny is registered.
German companies also legally copy each other in the same way, as has happened to the sporting goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet in which he keeps seats from the Beijing trademark office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that also used the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are multi-storey department stores dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch's cases are of a different nature. On behalf of his clients, he fights against the trademark office officially granting Chinese companies the right to profit from a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or companion brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
which refers to women who have "fished" a rich man.
Chinese authorities do not feel guilty
"It's detrimental to the business, you have to fight it," Pattloch demands.
"The brand is watering down, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage suffered by the image is enormous."
The financial losses and procedural costs of the affected sectors are millionaires, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15,000 million euros per year, China is, in size, the third market for luxury goods and the fastest growing.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of dubious legality in the registration of trademarks is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
The processes can take up to nine years and the outcome is uncertain.
Pattloch speaks of cases in which the court dismissed a claim because so much time had elapsed that the name that was the subject of the lawsuit had already become a "market reality."
"If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the process has damaged his trademark in China," Pattloch says.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That is why today the Chinese can continue to use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo's buyer, Geely, initially used a white and blue logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to amend it.
Clothing maker Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo depicted a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing acknowledges that in 2010 they have struggled due to a shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, "the labor emergency situation returned to normal."
In this way, the number of unprocessed claim processes has been reduced by 22%.
Almost 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims remain outstanding.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As usual in China, the figures are striking.
Last year the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means that China leads for the tenth consecutive year the list of new registrations worldwide, according to the trademark office.
It seems that this is also the case with the number of valid logos, a figure that amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan in royalties would have been pocketed.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the group has been fighting a Chinese impersonator in court.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the impersonator has managed to secure Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
"We ourselves have caused this situation because in Germany surnames are not protected," says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also dismissed the Munich appeal.
In the next two instances they have agreed with Freudenberg, but the opposite party continues to fight today.
You have to be very careful
Now the case has reached the doors of the Superior Court of Justice, where it is still pending.
Wentzler is confident that he can resolve the issue favorably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that "the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time."
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; The business archive has had to review files up to a hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposing party a "six-figure sum in euros" with the aim of reaching an amicable settlement, but he was unsuccessful.
"This shows how much we care," Wentzler says.
The dangers lurking in the Far East even threaten to affect Europe.
Specifically whether imitators secure rights to unprotected trademarks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The group has long since left this commercial area, but managed to prevent registration.
"You have to be very careful," Wentzler says.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch advise German companies to be extremely cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international legislation on trademark rights, but what must be done is "also register in China everything that may be eligible for protection," as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the topic can be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, should Freudenberg lose the last round of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party license fees in his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
