The tour of the mountainous region of Talysh could be described as wild and romantic.
The minibus makes its way through the winding road past wooded hills, high-flow rivers and the simple homes of local farmers.
Everything is green and juicy, one might even think that it is located in the Black Forest.
However, we are in the southernmost part of Azerbaijan; from here the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
Here live the "talyshi", a people of whom not much is known, apart from the fact that they perfectly dominate Persian and Azeri and that they are very long-lived.
Our final destination is Lerik.
This small town boasts perhaps too massive architecture designed in the Soviet era and does not seem to fit entirely into such a picturesque mountainous landscape.
European tourists hardly reach this place, as the road from the capital of Azerbaijan, Baku, is too heavy.
To travel the 323 kilometers that separate both urban centers, it takes eight hours because the road is one-way.
The staggering wealth the country enjoys from Caspian Sea oil has yet to reach this remote region.
However, Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has what it takes to become a tourist attraction.
"Baku became famous in May on the occasion of the Eurovision Song Contest and next year we will celebrate the World's Oldest People Festival," Fatulayeva said.
She is the director of the Museum of Longevity, perhaps the only one that exists in the world.
Here is documented the life of eight dozen talyshis of the place who have exceeded 100 years of age. Fatulayeva points to a black-and-white image.
This is my grandfather, who lived 120 years.
A son of his died at the age of 136
However, the undisputed star of the museum is the sheepherder Şirali Müslümov, who seems to have lived 168 years.
However, there is no birth certificate that certifies it.
And if we consider that the oldest documented man lived 122 years, it seems that Müslümov's age is quite suspicious.
"He was born in the region in 1805 and died in 1973," Fatulayeva explains.
The man was married three times and had 23 children. She apparently still had time to conceive one more daughter at the age of 136.
So has Şirali Müslümov been wrong in his age in a couple of decades?
However, Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, has also heard of the advanced age of this Central Asian inhabitant.
"In some regions of China, Japan or in the Hunza Valley in Pakistan there are also very elderly people," says Scholz, "even in Sardinia there are many older men."
Due to lack of documentation, it is impossible to provide scientific evidence about age; especially when there is no civil registry either.
