In a constantly connected world, it's not so bad to get a little bored
During this year's Thanksgiving holidays, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours in an airport because the plane we were flying on suffered a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I'm not going to lie to you.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is quite boring, even if you have means to be entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, not forgetting duty-free shops.
But more and more academics and child development experts are praising the benefits of boredom.
According to them, it is okay that both we and our children get bored from time to time.
Being bored forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we don't experience the benefits of boredom.
So, should we cheer up boredom?
Yes.
And no.
But, we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" published in 2011 by Yale University Press, says, this is not the case.
"In fact, the history of boredom is very extensive," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about boredom dating from the first century AD.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it's already been defined and discussed in many different ways," says John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the published research and pitching the idea to a 100-person discussion group, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "desiring, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fulfills you."
He states that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person doesn't do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do something.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "the disruption of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly."
Boredom can sound terribly like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that, although they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider that the problem is theirs.
Sometimes we think we are bored, when what really happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a journal article.
Some groups listened in the next room to a loud television program that was not related, others listened to it at low volume, so that it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not hear the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the program with the volume low showed more boredom than the other two groups; They struggled to concentrate, but they weren't sure why and attributed it to boredom.
"When you're trying to focus on a difficult or interesting task, impaired attention can lead to boredom," said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study's authors.
"On the other hand, when you're doing something boring, like spotting defective parts on a manufacturing line, distracting music can help you not get bored."
"In fact, we now know that moving or doodling, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help combat it, as they make that person physically more alert."
"Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to be still," says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it's like to be bored at some point: the delay of a plane, a monotonous speaker, an especially boring movie.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed a "boredom tendency scale" in the '80s.
The scale includes things like "many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "there are so many things I'm interested in that I don't have time to do it all."
Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that, using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external and more varied stimulation.
But in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 teens and their parents seven to eight times a day using a search.
It found that 32 percent of teens said they got bored while at school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they got bored when they weren't in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the current boring percentages, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that "adolescence is a period when boredom reaches its highest levels," largely because both children and teens aren't given much control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question from the beginning: is it good to get bored?
Sometimes it is not, since, taken to the extreme, it can expose us to absurd physical risks, such as making bets or falling into substance use as a method to combat it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this question for more than two decades.
"Boredom is the brain's way of telling you you you should be doing something else," says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what's most appropriate.
If you're bored and use that energy to play guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
"So, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may not be bored anymore, but he won't have learned to entertain himself or to dose himself," says Professor Fenske.
And "that ability to dose applies to other situations," he says.
Your child not only learns to entertain himself, but learns to control himself better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of it either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant buzz of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"In our view, we need to get more bored, but boredom is too distressing and disturbing a desire to relate to something worthwhile," he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a downtime.
"In an environment where we're constantly overstimulated," he says, "it's hard to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops."
