Petronella Wyatt: "I was harassed to Oxford for being a Tory"
College students are not attacked for their views only now
I can't remember a time in my life when I haven't been dreaming of getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and older brother had been to what I assumed was the best place in the world to learn, a contemporary Greek symposium that fostered the two pillars of civilization: free thought and tolerance.
However, two weeks after taking my place at Worcester College in the late 80s to study History, I had already packed my bags, which triggered the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and burst into tears.
My friends were puzzled.
The Evening Standard newspaper said I had dropped out because I couldn't tolerate some college classmates having sex in the next room.
The writer A. N. Wilson jokingly announced that I was leaving because I was forced to drink from chipped cups.
The truth was less fun.
I ran away from there.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my flamboyant name, nor the fact that it came from a private school.
I was harassed for only one reason, which in the cradle of the supposed enlightenment was somewhat bigoted and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the Conservative Party.
You may wonder what that is coming to now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of center-right students is suffering similar persecution.
The institutionalised and growing hatred of Conservative Party students is such in Oxford that, last week, a group of them demanded the same level of equal rights as gays, the disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the JCR (undergraduate student group) at Corpus Christi College say they are "often seriously sidelined, personally attacked and treated as persona non grata" for their political views.
They want to create a seat on their college's equal opportunity committee to make sure they can express their opinions freely.
Their situation was not helped by a recent BBC2 documentary called "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right" about student politics that portrayed the Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
It showed postgraduate student Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Party Association (OUCA), in a Rolls-Royce, sporting a silver suit and a cane with a silver hilt on it.
At other universities, conservative students say they are being treated as "scapegoats" for the introduction of higher tuition fees.
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the Conservative Party Association at the University of Nottingham, told a Sunday newspaper that "there is a growing left-wing trend in universities.
People assume we're like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other."
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student in Corpus Christi who introduced the motion for greater protection, says this environment is "uncomfortable," while Stephanie Cherill, 19, OUCA's president-elect, says the attitude of JCR members toward people who are center-right has worsened.
"This poses a threat to the intellectual debate environment, as well as to the well-being of the members," he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford I was more lonely than one.
I entered college in September 1986, I was a terribly shy 18-year-old.
Hatred of the Conservative Party was at an all-time high.
The previous year, the university had voted to deny Margaret Thatcher, a former student, an honorary degree following cuts in higher education funding.
The atmosphere would have made any Stalinist shudder with horror.
Already during the first days of the week of welcome to the new university students, when the new students meet and meet the professors, I received a sample of the bitterness that awaited me.
I found that professors not only turned a blind eye to the mockery of conservative university students, but willingly participated in it.
The politics of the miners' strike, privatisation and the government's opposition to anti-apartheid sanctions in South Africa reached the wooden rooms of the seminary.
The first one I attended, eighteenth-century French texts had to be translated into English and I was not prepared for what came next.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I didn't give a single one.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like cake dough, knew well how to expel bad bile.
"Are Thatcheites refusing to learn French or are they just fools?" he asked.
The other college students laughed.
My eyes burned from the tears I was trying to hold.
"I suggest you go to French classes in your spare time, as long as you're not too busy meeting people," Pitt growled.
I returned to my room like a soul in sorrow.
That night I sat alone at dinner time at the university. Then I felt a slight pat on the back.
He was a second-year English student named James who applied as a member of the OUCA.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
"I'm afraid that's how things go.
They mess with anyone suspected of being Tory.
For me it is very complicated, but they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so for you it will be even worse.
Many newcomers Tory appear to be Labour."
Later, in a local pub, I cowardly tried to disguise.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything Mrs Thatcher said.
That trick proved futile.
A first-year student of Philosophy, Politics and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton, said: "You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You are contaminated."
Other students adopted that little song.
I became the dirty pervert.
"How do the Tories have sex?" one asked.
"They beat each other up, don't they?"
I felt the same way homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the '60s.
Could I one day lead a normal life at Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I become a Labour Party and suppress my natural tendencies?
The three years that awaited me were presented as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory professor was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History assigned to my college.
They hated him for being not only from the Conservative Party, but also an adviser to Thatcher on foreign policy and one of the people who wrote his speeches for her.
I was barely there.
He detested the place because he considered it provincial and insignificant and because of its adherence to the Marxist-determinist vision of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You're not going to be happy here," he told me.
I began commuting from Oxford to my parents' home in London, finding refuge in my more open-minded Metropolitan family and friends.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He didn't believe me.
When he studied there in the 40s, all political points of view were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said sadly.
"They would never do that, not there among my beloved dream needles.
Even my communist friends always had an impeccable attitude."
His sore eyes began to cloud.
"Give it another chance.
I'm sure they've done it just to joke.
It would break my heart if you let him."
Exhausted from so many trips to London, my emotional stamina was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to pressure and renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar in which another history professor had insinuated, totally seriously, that I was an "enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Red with embarrassment inside, I admitted that my parents had "brainwashed" me and called them "stupid old men."
The truce was short-lived.
It was my father who put the final nail in the coffin of my university career at Oxford.
At that time my father wrote two weekly columns in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I was inside huddled in fear and, after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed my bags and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
Perhaps you call me a weak crybaby.
But no 18-year-old should be subjected to such a level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it was Oxford, which has not only trained 14 Conservative Party prime ministers but, to this day, hides behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
