The toughest trade in the world: Kawah Ijen's human mules
For four euros, the porters of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to go down every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfurous gas emanating from the bowels of the Earth solidifies when it comes into contact with the air.
After uprooting large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two bamboo baskets that he carries on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to ascend at a snail's pace, keeping their balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall off the cliff.
They know that any misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell years ago down the cliffs of the Kawah Ijen.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 euro cents for every kilo of sulphur they extract
Once up, they make their way among the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, wearily carrying the heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters high.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupiah (5 euro cents) for each kilo of sulfur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As it is normal to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three shipments a day.
It takes three hours each and ends up ground, but they allow him to collect 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems like a pittance for such an inhuman effort, it is triple what he would earn on the field.
"The miners' wage is very high here, where coffee picking is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros)," clarifies the porter, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the pit was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a compelling reason that, in Indonesia, is as forceful as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus,  and I have brought her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathes heavily, coughs constantly and has his eyes irritated by toxic fumes
At 27, Anto has been playing his skin for three years in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, breathes heavily, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that the volcano gives off.
It's the price you must pay to achieve your dream.
"I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this friendly and intelligent young man might be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead he does the job of a mule.
Sharing a filthy wooden cabin with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and glows in the middle of the darkness.
Braving the shadows, Anto descends into the crater with a small lantern attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
About 400 porters carry the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its huge profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs or supply any equipment to the porters, who work on their own and at both the weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera that, together with the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for the beasts and not for the people," protests Madrusin, a burly 42-year-old porter who has been at the Kawah Ijen for three decades, since leaving school.
Capable of lifting up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will endure working "as much as he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children, between 18 and 10 years old.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been all my life.
Although sulfur burns the throat and stinging the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that none complains of suffering serious diseases... Beyond, of course, their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, knee pain and shoulder sores, which have been malformed by the weight of the baskets.
Swinging the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at 53 years old.
Every day, he and his companions pluck 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks move to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away along a goat road through the undergrowth.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been all my life," Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth wide, where several teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30, also works loading sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest trades in the world: the one made by the human mules of the Kawah Ijen.
Singapore seeks babies to save economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress and the cost of property and education for not having children.
"Singapore's population needs to grow."
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, let's fulfill our civic duty and create life!
It may seem implausible that these verses are part of an advertisement for mint pills, but despite that – or perhaps because of it – the video went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The phrases are part of a rap that uses local references like "Let's put a bao (bun) in the oven" to laugh at Singapore's birth rate.
The advertising company that made the video, BBH, hopes that with the ad they will be able to draw attention to the problem in a fun way.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to do "their national duty."
This is purely internet, so we had to make it fun and funny.
It's the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world at reproducing ourselves, so we felt this was an issue we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried many things, such as launching perfumes with pheromones or organizing speed-dating evenings.
Many of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn't necessarily work.
So we thought, why don't we do as creative as we can to solve this problem, which is to write a rap?
1.2 children
The one that does not take it so lightly is the Singapore government.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for married couples and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and doles out tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its leaders' conservatism and strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, according to its national population division, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 – known as the replacement rate – was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Division, says it's because of "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities."
"That has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond getting married and starting a family," she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the rise of singleness, and to delaying marriage and births, resulting in a declining birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at drastically increasing immigration to cope with population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where thinly disguised xenophobia abounds against many new immigrants, particularly Chinese, whom they criticize for keeping wages low and not integrating.
Increased immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore's ruling party experienced its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the election there has been an attempt to correct the problem, with higher quotas and levies on foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has known effects on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, healthcare costs and immigration policies, the example of Singapore is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government tries not to build so many small houses.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has shifted to controlling the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have surfaces of 46 square meters and have been very successful sales.
However, there are concerns that they may promote a single-minded lifestyle and discourage developers who want to build large, family-owned homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate company EL Developers, says his "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger units.
They are more popular, in the sense that units run out days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new rules give clearer guidance for developers, who were previously hindered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step toward increasing the national birth rate, talking to Singaporeans working in the downtown financial district doesn't seem like they're going to have much effect.
"People are very stressed, houses are expensive and so is education, so many people are putting it off," says one young executive.
Other people may have children.
"But it's important for me to have my own money and time," says another young man in his 20s.
Men and women cite their career, stress, and the cost of property and education as the reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, as much as the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans have the final say.
Private off line is private online
Privacy.
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy it is the quality of private or "the field of private life that you have the right to protect from any interference".
What is private for a child under 16?
How do you apply this definition in your everyday life and on social media?
Do you understand the dangers you're exposed to by airing situations on the Internet that you probably wouldn't share offline?
elPeriódico interviewed five boys between ten and 15 years old, frequent users of the network.
In four of the cases, they associated the term with "something very mine", on a personal level, and "in the user's password and name", when applied to social networks.
"I wouldn't upload my deepest secrets to a post," says ten-year-old Jorge as he tries to explain the meaning of private on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They are very secret secrets, my mom can know them, but not everyone," he says.
On FB I upload beautiful images or games.
I also entertain myself with my acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that's not mine, or of someone making a fool of themselves," he says.
The child recognizes that it is wrong to post obscene photographs, nude people, crimes or write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge claims to know the 35 friends he has on FB and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most are relatives.
The mother is included, she has the key to one of the accounts.
I opened Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they answer me, I just upload them," he adds.
"Social media is entertaining, I can talk to distant relatives or my friends quickly," he says.
He does not hesitate to answer that he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
Nor would he listen to someone who recommended him to a stranger.
The case of José, 14, is different.
The teenager has accounts opened on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, in the latter he admits not knowing 20 of the people added to his friends list.
"It doesn't scare me, because we have something in common, music for example," he says.
According to the boy, no one has insinuated to him or asked for his home address or phone number.
"If they pressure me or demand it, I would simply take them out of my account," he admits.
Jose became a follower of Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is no stranger to the experiences of what is now known as cyberbullying.
An acquaintance of a friend of my friend was being extorted on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who he was," she says.
The victim, according to José, did not close the account.
"He just put privacy on it."
It then explains a series of steps to set up the account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this guy would upload photos of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
Yes I would, if I don't like it or I feel like it.
"Even though I know that's cyberbullying," he says.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, English teacher and graduate in Education and Learning, believes that to guide children and adolescents it must be understood that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet emerged as a means to search for information, but with the appearance of these sites the rules of the game changed," he says.
Porras points out that academic Marc Prensky, a master's degree in Pedagogy from Yale University and author of the work Digital Natives and Immigrants, coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are them, the children and young people who were born with technology.
"We are the digital immigrants we have to teach them, when we are still learning," he says.
He comments that the issue is complex, "because we are asking them to have a defined criterion on what should or should not be disseminated, published or said at an age that maturity does not give for that."
"Also to be selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach privacy to children and adolescents is through questions that make them reflect.
"Telling them not to do it doesn't work," he adds.
Below, Porras lists some options: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, why do you do it online?
Or, would you like them to post a photo of you like the one you posted of a friend?
Do you know what others post about you?
When you tag party photos, did you ask other people for permission to tag them?
And one more, does everyone need to know what you're doing every moment?
Another point is to make them see that they should act online as they do offline.
They are the same rules.
"One outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, the same should be in social networks," he says.
Vigilance
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educational consultant, says that it is essential for parents to read the politics of social networks thoroughly.
By understanding each of the subparagraphs, they have a solid foundation for talking with their children about the implications of opening an online account.
"For example, age and what is allowed to be shared or posted," he says.
According to Guardia, it is key to remind children of the lesson of "don't talk to strangers."
Unasur Summit ends without making public the Lima Declaration
The VI Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without making public the Declaration of Lima, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven attending presidents.
Efe repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources from the Foreign Ministry and the Presidency initially said that they were going to deliver it after the closing, but later they affirmed that at some point it will be published on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When asked about the text, they pointed out that the content had been exposed by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to Summit information was restricted throughout.
During the day, only the video without sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among the reporters was delivered by the press spokesmen of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian one.
The only document released during the day was the list of attending presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the Presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it is Humala's pronouncement, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the III South America-Arab Countries Summit (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced was not disseminated either.
On the official website of ASPA it can be corroborated that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international events, the Peruvian authorities made efforts to ensure that transmission systems were secured for all journalists but limited the obtaining of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Court of The Hague that settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (ICJ), which begins on Monday in The Hague to hear the arguments of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
"We will abide by and execute the sentence that defines the differences that we are bringing today to this international court," Humala said, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international courts," Piñera added, greeting Humala with a handshake, next to the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ occurred after Colombia denounced this week the Pact of Bogotá by which it had agreed to submit to the rulings of that international court, following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered seriously erroneous.
The summit was held with the absences of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit, shortly after noon in Lima.
The president read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and the lines of action were set for 31 projects among South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship for which we are expanding residency agreements."
He reported that actions are being promoted to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, access to low-priced internet in all corners of South America, and jointly and efficiently address the risks of natural disasters."
With a Europe in crisis, "the economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a triumphalist matrix but should serve to expand our productive matrix and glimpse a better future for our peoples," Humala added.
"We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," the Peruvian president said in a message read.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for his reincorporation into the Union of South American Nations," from which he is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated, and good relations between neighbors, was another of the issues highlighted by the summit.
In this sense, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to respectfully discuss the maritime dispute after a ruling of the ICJ, questioned by Bogota.
"Tomorrow (Saturday) it is possible that he will have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We are going to review all these paths, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua," he said.
"With President Ortega I hope to be able to tell him to handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega are expected to meet Saturday in Mexico where they plan to attend the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also, as part of the summit, the defense ministers of the bloc met previously to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defense in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of UNASUR, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
