At the moment, this ruling is not being complied with.
It is a problem between a South American country and a Central American one.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the willingness to walk together.
You have to process them in a broad way to overcome them and move forward.
He also hoped for a good conclusion of the litigation for maritime limits that Peru and Chile maintain in the same court and said that "it is correct for Latin America to seek international instances if the two countries commit to accept a ruling, no matter how harsh it may be."
In reference to the eventuality that he presents himself as a candidate in the next presidential elections in Ecuador to seek a third consecutive term, he said that he sees that possibility "with a lot of optimism and joy, although sometimes it is quite hard."
Correa said that if he loses the February 2013 elections he will retire from public life.
Personally, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unfair as Ecuador, that socioeconomic poverty can only be corrected from political power.
"My political movement believed that it was me who guaranteed that probable victory, because we have to accept that responsibility," he said.
If I win, it would be my last term in the presidency and from there we left public life.
If we lose the same.
"It's a decision," he said.
Correa also referred to Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez's new health treatment in Cuba.
I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he tells me that he traveled to a treatment that was already planned, routine, that the campaign was expected to pass to return to Cuba.
"It does not mean a relapse in the state of health of President Chavez," he said.
