AIDS deaths are now cause of late detection
Fabrizio was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed: AIDS positive.
"It was as if a bomb fell on me," he says when recalling the moment of the announcement, which the doctor was trying to make "softer", without obvious success.
The boy hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to inform himself about it; With such determination that he already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is, without a doubt, one of the oldest patients in the HIV Unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), which he arrived in 1994 after several battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 90s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
Then, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he had a cut."
So, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and do so with quality of life.
However, ignorant of their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already wreaked havoc, "depleted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, at least of the first reported cases, "the great achievement means at this time that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population, is exactly the same," said the head of the HIV Unit of HCG.  Jaime Andrade Villanueva, after referring that this information was endorsed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectologist and expert in HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists had concluded that AIDS was not a fatal sentence, but the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of involvement to the immune system that patients present at the beginning of the diagnosis, with better expectations for those who are not drug users:  up to 30 years with a CD4 count of 200 and 50 years, when they report 500 CD4.
In simple words, this means that those who receive the diagnosis of HIV positive at 25 years of age, under these terms "as long as they remain in control will be able to live without problems until the age of 75," explained the interviewee.
To measure this progress, it should be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years on average.
While mortality has dropped significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS dropped from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60 percent of patients in the national database have died.
Only in Jalisco 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths until May of this year; However, it is ensured that there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still deaths?
- It seems to me that the problem is not access to treatment.
That's how I visualize it, that's how it has happened to us in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years we have not had a shortage of medicine, the problem is that patients arrive very advanced because they do not know their state of infection, that is, in late stages of the disease.
He gave a blunt fact: "Nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what has to be done to have a greater impact on global mortality, is to make earlier diagnoses and, therefore, detection tests have to be offered massively, to all people who require it. "
In his proposal, specialists and officials of the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco (Coesida) agree, also the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who went to a private laboratory to be tested, only motivated because a friend had done it and, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS stage and even suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma,  A cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they are going to die and don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, I'd better blow myself three times a week," they say not in my case.
The change was for the better, I eat well, I exercise, I take the medicines.
To date, his parents only know that he suffered from cancer.
I live a normal life, like anyone else.
"I work, I have many activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I take care of myself and the other person," said Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to motivate with his testimony those who today, in the framework of World AIDS Day, are afraid.
That they get tested, if they were at risk, that the sooner they know if they are HIV positive, the better and if they already have the diagnosis, that they learn that they can live like anyone, being responsible.
That, his message, sums up the motto of the battle against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are large gaps between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken up the cause around HIV.
And the biggest one is in prevention.
In the places dedicated to this task "effectively the distribution of condoms has increased, before they gave us one or two, now they give us packages of a hundred, and that is very good but it turns out that there are those who today, still, do not have access to a condom," he said.
Among those most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
"What do you want them for?" is a common question, with sarcasm and value judgments from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy employees and health personnel, to which adolescents do not want to be exposed, said the communicator.
He proposed to reorient this inefficient distribution; That condoms are not only behind the counters and those hundred are in dispatchers of public toilets in the places frequented by young people.
It is not motivating promiscuity.
Nor is it about paying them the chelas and the motel, as Governor Emilio González replied, when asked if there would be distribution of condoms in his Administration.
"That's not how sexuality is, it's best to bring condoms to those who already practice sexual activity," he said.
Keys In Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 of AIDS and 1,317 of HIV).
The state ranks 4th nationally in new and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th in HIV.
92% of infections correspond to the sexual route, 6% to the blood route and 2% to the perinatal route.
It is estimated that 50 thousand people may be living with HIV since for a registered case there are 4 to 5 people who do not know it.
