Few people in Puerto Rico have as broad a mental collection of local basketball history as Hector "Hetin" Reyes has.
Before a stroke confined him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a player of minor categories, player of the National Superior Basketball, proxy and leader in the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the Basketball Federation.
"I wore many basketball hats throughout my life, including several at the same time, such as when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the National Team and federation president during the 90s," Reyes recalled during a Primera Hora visit to his home in Bayamón, where he resides with Isabel, his faithful wife of more than 50 years.
"Basketball has been my life."
Reyes is not exaggerating in making that assertion.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memorabilia that denote his extensive career, testify to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all, the ones he treasures with the most emotion are those that recall his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, when he turned 15 years serving as a co-agent or proxy of the franchise.
"Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most because I had the opportunity to be part of eight Cowboys championships since 1967, whether as a proxy, co-agent or manager.
There were many years of satisfaction, including the five championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye with one in 1981, Jerome Mincy's debut year at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took over," Reyes said.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had coached here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me, "I have a very strong player, 6"7" tall.
