Actor Larry Hagman dies
Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Fort Worth (Texas), became world famous for his central role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R", in the television series "Dallas", in which he played an unscrupulous, malicious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predatory oil tycoon J.R. Ewing on the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday afternoon of complications from cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., the production house of "Dallas."
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again playing the iconic role he loved most," the family said.
Larry's family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for the Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, her publicist, Jeffrey Lane, said.
He brought joy to everyone he met.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, caring and talented, and I will miss him dearly.
"He was an original person and lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and acknowledged that he had drunk heavily for years.
In 1995 a malignant tumor was found in his liver and he underwent a transplant.
Years before "Dallas," Hagman became famous on television as a decent guy in the light comedy "I Dream of Jeannie," which aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life is altered when he finds an attractive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and takes her to live with him at his house.
He also starred in two comedies that were short on the air, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included critically acclaimed roles in "The Group," "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors."
But it was his masterful portrayal of the charmingly obnoxious J.R. that propelled Hagman to ultimate stardom.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its orbit ran from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional phrase "Who shot J.R.?", designed to generate expectation around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is almost killed, generated international speculation and millions of dollars risky in bookmakers.
It also helped give the series a record audience at the time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers tuned in and made "Dallas" the second-most-watched entertainment show in history, behind the end of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. impregnated her and then threatened to call her a prostitute unless she left town, but others also had reason to attack him.
Hagman portrayed Ewing as an insatiable corrupt man with a charismatic smile: a cheating businessman and a cheating husband who tried to get his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), hospitalized.
"I know what I want on J.R.'s tombstone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should say, "Here lies the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only deal he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, on Friday remembered Hagman as someone "huge, on and off screen."
He is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each of us, who were lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success for the TNT channel.
He had already finished recording five of the episodes for the second season and a sixth was in process, the network reported.
There was no immediate comment from Warner or TNT on how the series will handle Hagman's loss.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who starred in classic plays such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan."
Martin was still a teenager when she had it in 1931 during her marriage to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He tried his hand at the New York theater stage in the early 1950s, and then served in the Air Force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
While there he met the young Swedish designer Maj Axelsson and married her.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for a long time in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001 he titled his memoir "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life".
"I didn't put anything there that I believed was going to hurt someone or affect them in any way," he told the Associated Press at the time.
After the liver transplant he became a promoter of organ donation and volunteered at a hospital to assist fearful patients.
"I counsel them, I give them courage, I meet with them when they come for their surgeries, and afterward," he said in 1996.
I try to offer some comfort, like "fear not, it will be a little awkward for a brief while, but you're going to be fine."
He was also an anti-smoking activist and participated in several campaigns.
Course that explores the "End of the World" begins
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible hook: The end of the "long countdown" of the Mayan Calendar, on December 21, to which many people have clung as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what awaited him in the next couple of months: The cataclysmic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal cliff that some have called "debtrmagedon" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian end-times theorists believe the apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University this week.
If you look at what's been happening in the world today as if we're 30 days away and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember that bad is good for those of apocalyptic mentality.
And he is not the only professor offering courses on the "end of the world" this semester, theoretically the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World."
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We looked at why these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month students analyzed movies with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare to real-life examples.
"I've tried to inform students about what's possible, likely, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an adjunct professor of art history and anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, titled only "The End of the World."
"We didn't add '2012' to always have the option to teach the course again, in case the world doesn't end," Restill said.
Despite the "imminent ruin", students must study, generate projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the very night the world is supposed to end," Restill said.
The courses proved quite popular.
"It was saturated in two hours," Restall said of his course for high-GPA students, which was filled with 35 students.
We received emails for weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, from people asking if there was still room.
The students, on the other hand, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves," said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, in Rutgers-Camden.
And it is that the apocalyptic mentality, secular or religious, is only a matter of consolation or the absence of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he has seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of a class that could teach that," he said.
I enjoy it.
But no student interviewed — let alone a professor — said they believed the Dec. 21 expiration date.
"Our first project was about Mayan prophecy and we kind of debunked it," said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior at Temple from West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key item on the calendar, Restill said.
But he noted that there is apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, dating back several centuries, in which people react to changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a boom in these speculations.
"Elsewhere people don't think about this," he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a religion professor at La Salle University who teaches courses in the Philippines this year, was quick to answer the question of whether he knew about any courses on the "end of the world" there.
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world," he wrote, hinting at an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been talk of many doomsday days, and said that if nothing happens on Dec. 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that Dec. 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said they plan to go to parties "at the end of the world."
"Maybe I'll call some friends so we can laugh together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
